h a provocatively Marxian framing that reveals these two writers shared more in common about agency and society than has previously been recognized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMiscegenation. 0aRacially mixed people in literature. 0aRacially mixed peoplexPsychology. 0aReunionese literature (French)xHistory and criticism. 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aDirlik, Arif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEze, Emmanuel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791480359423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791480359/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles